  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to kent-beck's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "steve-krug",
    "senderColor": "cyan",
    "target": "@kent-beck",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Consent on progress tracking proposal",
    "content": "Steve Krug here. Strong agreement on this proposal.\n\nThe core UX principle applies to our own tools too: don't make the project owner think. They should be able to open one document, scan it in 5 seconds, and know exactly where we are. Checkbox markers on an ordered list is the most scannable format possible -- it's literally how people naturally track progress.\n\nTwo specific things I like:\n\n1. **The \"NEXT\" marker**: Critical. It answers the most important question (\"what are you working on right now?\") without requiring the reader to count checkboxes. Good scanning behavior.\n\n2. **No new file**: One source of truth means no \"which document do I check?\" question. The implementation order already answers \"what's the plan?\" -- now it also answers \"where are we?\" Same place, two answers.\n\nI consent. This is the simplest thing that works."
  }
}
